Cryptoasset Analysis using Signed Betas

Karim Helmy: karim@timelock.cc

11/13/2019

Summary

Formal analysis of the cryptoasset space is still in its infancy, and to our knowledge there has not yet been a differentiation between downside and upside performance of assets. In this report, we perform an analysis on the upside and downside \(\beta\) and \(\alpha\) of Bitcoin Cash (BCH), Ether (ETH), Monero (XMR), and ZCash (ZEC) with respect to Bitcoin. We find that these assets are all much more exposed to Bitcoins changes in price during downturns than they are during upswings, and additionally have negative independent returns during downturns, both of which are factors leading to general decreased performance.

Motivation

Bitcoin has outperformed most other large-cap cryptocurrencies in the last year. To observe this, consider the the graph below, showing the price of cryptocurrencies in the period from 12 November 2018 to 12 November 2019 as a percentage of their starting value in that period.

Simply put, this graph can be interpreted as answering the following question: if I allocated 100 USD into each of the following assets at the start date, how many dollars would that be worth today? Because the value-per-unit of each asset is on such a different scale, this type of comparison is the only meaningful way to compare price. The differences in performance are quite stark: Bitcoin (BTC) is the only asset of those considered that would have yielded a positive return, with a return of 39.86%. The returns on Ether (ETH), Monero (XMR), Bitcoin Cash (BCH), and ZCash (ZEC) were -7.65%, -37.16%, -43.44%, and -70.75%.

Somewhat paradoxically, however, the performance of the cryptoasset space is highly correlated with that of Bitcoin, its largest constituent currency. This can be visually confirmed in the graph below, tracking the daily change in price of the studied assets as a percentage of their start price.

Numerically, this is confirmed as well: the correlations between Bitcoin and Ether, Bitcoin Cash, Monero, and ZCash are 0.80, 0.73, 0.71, 0.66, respectively. These values correspond to moderately high correlation, in the case of ZCash, to high correlation, in the case of the of all other assets, between the assets and the benchmark.

Methodology and Results

To identify where this differentiation occurs, we study the relative performance of each asset during Bitcoins upside and downside periods. We identify each assets coefficient of systemic risk, or \(\beta\), benchmarked against the performance Bitcoin. We then decompose \(\beta\) into upside \(\beta\) (\(\beta^+\)) and downside \(\beta\) (\(\beta^+\)), considering only the days on which Bitcoins returns were positive and negative, respectively. For each asset, we then derive \(\alpha\), \(\alpha^+\), and \(\alpha^-\), the excess returns on the corresponding days calculated using the corresponding systemic risk, for the sake of simplicity using a risk-free rate of 0. The results of these calculations are shown in the table below.

Symbol Beta Alpha Upside Beta Upside Alpha Downside Beta Downside Alpha
BTC 1.0000000 0.0000000 1.0000000 0.0000000 1.0000000 0.0000000
BCH 0.4639511 -0.6193938 0.3676350 0.5274245 0.5022468 -0.3525320
ETH 0.6826553 -0.3486958 0.4703435 1.6705356 0.7719642 -0.2408934
XMR 0.4712485 -0.5594726 0.2551333 1.7493488 0.5304743 -0.6765360
ZEC 0.3492895 -0.8468293 0.1968027 0.9399903 0.4028134 -0.5692125

Analyzing these results, we find that \(\beta^-\) significantly exceeds \(\beta^+\) for each altcoin. This indicates that each altcoin in the study is more exposed to Bitcoins downturns than to its upswings. On decomposition, the negative \(\alpha\) is shown to be a result of this increased exposure, in combination with a negative \(\alpha^-\), and despite a positive \(\alpha^+\).

These results lead us to conclude that the poor altcoin market performance occurs as a result of both greater exposure to Bitcoins downside than upside, and an independent negative return in downside situations.

Implications

The methodology described here is generalizable to other baskets of currenciesfor example, it would be interesting to see an analysis of the performance of ERC20 tokens benchmarked against that of Ether, or a comparison of various stablecoins risk against that of Tethers USDT. Differentiating between upside and downside risk is critical in times of systemic crisis, and we hope to that this differentiation becomes standard practice in the cryptoasset space as the industry matures.
